# ITIL

- Not Meeting Service Level Agreement (SLA)
- Frequent Major incidents 
- Constant Fire-fighting
- Infrastructure not capable of absorbing new changes 
- Unplanned Outages/ Security incidents (Major virus attack)
- Infrastructure not capable of handling load at peak hours
- Lack of Governance structure
- Team working of trial and error method 


## Why service management for IT
- Most organizations today rely on IT to enable them to achieve their company vision, business strategy and goals
- Down time in IT huge business losses
    - Users rushed to branches when ATM was unable to dispense cash
 
## The benefits of adopting ITIL
- 
- ITIL helps IT Service Provider to build and manage their IT service capabilites in alignment to the business strategy and customer needs of the organization
- Implementation of ITIL processes has helped to have process driven support model as against person dependent 

## Evolution of ITIL 
- ITIL V1
    - 1980
    - IT Infrastructure system management
    - Focused on infrastructure stability and control

- ITIL V2
    - 2001
    - IT service management view
    - Service delivery and service support apporach

- ITIL V3 2011 
    - 2011
    - Focus remain as V3
    - Updated for more clarity, consistency and progress segregation 
    - 27 processes and 4 functions
- ITIL V4 
    - Aligned to 4th Industrial Resolution
    - Focus shift from process to practice
    - 34 practices 
    - Service value system
    - Align Agile DevOps and Lean principles  

## ITIL 4 First Glance
- Holistic Service Management apporach
    - Brings together ITSM Development, Operations, Business Relationships and governance along with its functions
- Strategic Position
    - Focuses on managing services during "forth industrial revolution" characterized by digital transformation. Digital Service Management Capability 
- Integration of various frameworks
    - Provides a practical and flexible foundation for organizations to integrate across frameworks and apporaches like Agile, DevOps, Lean, IT governance and so on 
- Outcome Oriented
    - Suggests a simple and pragmatic apporach focusing on creating value and desired outcome for customers  
- Co-create value

## Introduction to ITIL 
- Vendor Neutrality: Applicable to any IT organization because they are not based on any particular technology platform or industry type
- Non Prescriptive: Recommends an apporach of adopt and adapt to meet the specific needs of individual organizations. 


## Service Management
- Best Practice: Best practice is what, through experience and research, has proven to be relibly led to a desired result
- Good Practice: Good practice is what majority would find acceptable and achievable in terms of Quality versus cost 
- Function: A team or group of people and the tools they use to carry out one or more processes or activities 
- Roles: A set of responsibilites, activities and authorities granted to a person or team
- Service Provider: An organization supplying services to one or more internal or external customers. 

## Service 
- A means of enabling value co-creation by facilitating outcomes that customers want to achieve withour the customer having to own or manage specific costs and risks

- Product: Configuration of organizational resources designed to offer value to its customers


## Service Management
- Set of specialised organizational capabilities for enabling value for customers in the form of services. 
- Performed through 
    - People 
    - Process 
    - Information Technology
- The capabilities represent a service's organization's __Capacity, Competency and Confidence__ for action 

## Service Organizations
- Organization: A person or group that has its own functions with responsibilities, authorities and relationships to achieve its objectives. 
- Service Providers
    - When provisioning services, an organization takes on the role of the service provider 
- Service consumers
    - Customers/ Consumers

__Service offering:__ A formal description of one or more serices, designed to address the needs of a target consumer group 

__Goods__: Procure Server Hardware, Operating System, Database Licenses
- __Access to resources__: Activate Licence by registering product
- __Service Actions__: Install and configure

## Value
- Purpose of an organization is to create value for its stakeholders
- Value: The perceived benefits, usefulness and relavence/ importance of something. Outcome facilitated
- Value Co-creation: Through active collaboration between providers 

## Four Dimensions of Service Management

Acronym: __PESTLE__

## Service Value System (SVS)
- SVS describes how all components and activities of the organization work together as a system to enable value creation

![](https://www.axiossystems.com/hubfs/Figure-1.1-on-Page-3-of-ITIL-Foundation..png)

Guiding Principles: reccomendations that can guide an organization in all circumstances
Governance: is by the means with which an organization is directed and controled

SVC is a set of interconnected activities that an organization performs in order to deliver a valuable product or service to its consumers and to facilitate value realization

## ITIL 4 Seven Guiding Principles
- 1. Focus on Value
    - Customer experience
    - Anything that the organization does need to map directly or indirectly to value for the stakeholders   
- 2. Start Where You Are
    - Do not start from scratch
    - Leverage what is available
    - Apply risk management
    - Current state to be investigated and observed
- 3. Progress Iteratively with Feedback
- 4. Collaborate and promote visiblility 
- 5. Think and work Holistically  
- 6. Keep it simple and practical
    - Ensure every activity contributes to value
    - Use outcomes based thinking
    - Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication  
- 7. Optimize and Automate 
    - Simplify and optimize before automation
